Under Ohio Revised Code Section 5721.20, after the sale is confirmed and notice is given, any residue that remains unclaimed for 90 days after final notice is paid into the county treasury. The proper owner may then demand those funds from the county treasurer for up to three years from the date the treasurer receives them.

To support a claim, you will generally need to show the interest you held in the property at the time of sale and provide whatever additional documentation the county requests. Because the notice and transfer process can involve both the clerk of court and the county treasurer, it is worth confirming the current status with both offices.

If you choose to work with someone to help pursue the funds, review the fee terms carefully before signing anything.

Because Ohio's notice and treasury-transfer deadlines are firm, we recommend acting promptly and speaking with an Ohio-licensed attorney if you believe you have a valid interest. We are happy to review the county records with you and explain what documentation is typically required. This letter is informational only and is not legal advice.

